WEBVTT

00:11.180 --> 00:16.680
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:19.520 --> 00:21.220
And here are your hosts.

00:25.180 --> 00:32.900
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. In addition to being an author, Terry Carr
is one of science fiction's premier editors. We asked him how he got hooked on

00:32.900 --> 00:34.980
science fiction back in the late 1940s.

00:57.340 --> 01:04.840
We'd go down and look around to see what people were throwing out. And one day,
among the things we found people had thrown out were a couple of old pulp

01:04.840 --> 01:15.000
magazines from the year before. Amazing Stories. And I think there was one
Amazing Stories and one Fantastic Adventures, those being companion magazines.

01:16.180 --> 01:25.760
We grabbed those and brought them home. And I loved them. I got hooked right
there. After publishing a couple early novels and some short stories, Carr began

01:25.760 --> 01:37.720
his editing career at Ace Books. We asked him if he could tell us exactly what
he did for Ace. Yeah. In 1964, I went to work for Ace Books as an editorial

01:37.720 --> 01:49.360
assistant, which actually meant that I was low man
on the totem pole there. I was simply somebody who copyedited manuscripts, went

01:49.360 --> 01:54.280
over them to make sure the spelling was correct and things like that. There were
no typographical errors.

01:57.880 --> 02:07.640
And proofread the books before they actually got published to make sure, once
again, that there were no typographical errors in the typesetting. I would write

02:07.640 --> 02:18.840
blurbs, cover copies, kind of, you know, the things that are written on the
front and back covers of paperback books to try to get you to be interested

02:18.840 --> 02:28.560
enough in the book to buy it. And at the same time, I was reading a number of
submissions that were coming in. And if I saw something good, I would pass it on

02:28.560 --> 02:30.200
to the editor. It was Donald Wollheim.

02:39.100 --> 02:47.320
Carr says he then began to make suggestions for improving and expanding the Ace
line of science fiction books. And he worked his way up in the company. Ace

02:47.320 --> 02:56.340
Books then did start doing a number of the things that I had suggested. So that
I began getting this and that promotion. And I think after about the first three

02:56.340 --> 02:58.300
years, I became a senior editor there.

03:01.260 --> 03:09.840
And began a series called the Ace Science Fiction Specials, which was very much
a departure for Ace Books in particular, but for the entire field for that

03:09.840 --> 03:21.260
matter, because it was specifically designed to publish adult science fiction
novels, not simply juvenile adventure, but serious novels using the science

03:21.260 --> 03:33.480
fiction genre as its format, and packaged uniformly so that people would be able
to recognize a new book in the series when it came out, and packaged in such a

03:33.480 --> 03:43.220
way that, you know, it didn't have monsters chasing half-naked women on the
covers. We had very good artwork by a team of artists called Leo and Diane

03:43.220 --> 03:56.700
Dillon, who later won a Hugo Award and won two Caldecott Awards. God knows what
else. They are extremely good artists. I also began anthologizing very early

03:56.700 --> 04:10.160
when I started there. Don Wollheim and I were collaborating on an anthology, an
annual anthology, called World's Best Science Fiction. And I gradually branched

04:10.160 --> 04:23.940
out from that since I had begun to have my name on anthologies. I began to do
all this for Doubleday and Fawcett Books and so on. And that was actually how I

04:23.940 --> 04:33.100
got my start doing anthologies, was the work that I was doing in Ace Books. Some
of the anthologies Carr does include the Annual Universe series of Original

04:33.100 --> 04:41.980
Science Fiction, which he originated in 1971, and the Best Science Fiction of
the Year series, which he began in 1972. We'll talk to Terry Carr next time

04:41.980 --> 04:44.380
about what it's like to edit anthologies of science fiction.

04:51.700 --> 04:59.680
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

04:59.680 --> 05:02.080
Odessa, Texas.

05:42.800 --> 05:50.340
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:03.060 --> 06:08.440
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:11.440 --> 06:12.920
And here are your hosts.

06:17.260 --> 06:18.480
This is David Carson.

06:18.740 --> 06:19.460
And Daryl Lane.

06:19.720 --> 06:22.860
Each year, Terry Carr edits two of the best known anthologies in science fiction.

06:23.320 --> 06:28.300
One is the Universe series, begun in 1971, which is an anthology of original science fiction.

06:28.740 --> 06:35.220
We ask Carr the difference to an author between selling his story to a monthly science fiction magazine or selling it to an anthology like universe.

06:36.060 --> 06:37.480
There are all sorts of differences.

06:41.220 --> 06:43.680
They're both artistic and monetary differences.

06:44.420 --> 06:52.920
For one thing, if you sell to a magazine, then the money that you get from the magazine is simply the payment for that use of the story.

06:53.760 --> 06:56.900
If you sell it to an original anthology, that's going into a book,

06:57.380 --> 07:06.820
and you get an advance payment. But after that, you get a share of the
royalties. If the book sells well, then there will be additional earnings on the

07:06.820 --> 07:16.600
book, and the individual authors will continue to make money for years
thereafter, and indeed they do on Universe, because it does sell pretty well. So

07:16.600 --> 07:29.460
your chances of making money on your story are at least as good, I would say, in
the original anthologies as they are in the science fiction magazines. Aside

07:29.460 --> 07:41.180
from that, there's also the fact that a lot of writers simply like to have their
work appear in book form, because they know it's going to be around to be read

07:41.180 --> 07:47.400
longer than a magazine will be. It'll stay in better shape, and it'll be in
libraries and things like that.

07:55.740 --> 08:03.600
The Best Science Fiction of the Year, which Carr began in 1972 with Donald
Wollheim, is a different sort of anthology. It consists of stories published in

08:03.600 --> 08:10.700
science fiction magazines during the year. Carr reads all the magazines, then
selects those stories he considers to be the best. But he says that there are

08:10.700 --> 08:17.420
certain problems that he has to solve when he actually starts putting the
stories together. I do want to be sure that there aren't too many stories that

08:17.420 --> 08:25.860
are downbeat and depressing, because that's just not fun to read. They may be
good stories individually, but you just string them all end to end, and they can

08:25.860 --> 08:37.440
actually seem not as good as they are. So I try to work on that kind of balance,
and I try to mix up the balance between longer stories and shorter stories,

08:37.900 --> 08:47.480
because people do like variety in that. And if it should ever happen, for
instance, that I think the best 15 stories of the year, however many it takes,

08:49.000 --> 08:58.400
are all time travel stories, for instance, I'm not going to publish a whole book
full of time travel stories. That's just silly. Again, people would get tired of

08:58.400 --> 09:10.320
reading so many time travel stories in one book. So I try to mix up the themes,
too. Carr explains the particular needs an anthology fulfills. As best I know,

09:10.460 --> 09:22.540
an anthology fills a need for people who want to read good science fiction short
stories, novelettes, novellas, whatever. People who want to read something other

09:22.540 --> 09:31.980
than a novel. Probably people who want to have something that they can dip into
from time to time, rather than sitting down and reading the whole thing straight

09:31.980 --> 09:41.100
through as they would a novel. There's a different psychology between reading
novels and short stories, and most people do prefer to read novels. They always

09:41.100 --> 09:53.460
sell better than anthologies or single-author short story collections. But there
are people who like the short stories. I do, for instance. And they're the

09:53.460 --> 10:04.260
people who buy these. On a reprint anthology, the attraction, I think, is that
these stories have been doubly screened. They're stories that were good enough

10:04.260 --> 10:14.360
in the first place to sell to the magazine. And beyond that, they are the best
stories from the magazine. So the people who pick up an anthology can reasonably

10:14.360 --> 10:22.180
expect that that is going to contain more good stories than the average issue of
a science fiction magazine. This isn't always true. There's very bad

10:22.180 --> 10:31.880
anthologies, and there's very good issues in magazines. But far and large, that
is the case, I think. Terry Carr also writes fine science fiction. Next time,

10:31.900 --> 10:33.480
we'll talk to him about some of his own writing.

10:41.340 --> 10:49.280
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:49.280 --> 10:50.060
Odessa, Texas.

11:32.900 --> 11:36.880
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:52.980 --> 11:58.240
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:01.080 --> 12:02.640
And here are your hosts.

12:06.840 --> 12:14.340
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Among the science fiction anthologies that
Terry Carr has edited over the years are the so-called specialized anthologies.

12:14.560 --> 12:22.520
These would be volumes of short stories with a particular theme uniting them.
For example, a book of short stories on robots or time travel. Carr has done

12:22.520 --> 12:30.960
many special anthologies. We spoke with him about a few of them. He explains the
rationale behind his 1966 anthology, Science Fiction for People Who Hate Science

12:30.960 --> 12:44.420
Fiction. That was my first anthology that I did under my own name and nobody
else's name. It was, I think, back to the second anthology I did right after the

12:44.420 --> 12:53.480
first World's Best Science Fiction. And the idea on it was I wanted a book that
could be given to people who don't normally read science fiction, who think that

12:53.480 --> 12:54.280
they wouldn't like it.

12:57.280 --> 13:06.280
And I wanted, first, that the stories should be good stories. And second, that
the stories should be accessible to people who don't know the specialized

13:06.280 --> 13:15.720
language of science fiction. There are a whole lot of assumptions that are just
automatic in science fiction and nobody bothers to explain them anymore. So

13:15.720 --> 13:22.800
there are a lot of stories that are published these days that really require a
certain amount of background in reading science fiction in order to understand

13:22.800 --> 13:32.080
them. I mean, nobody stops to explain what a star warp drive is anymore because
that gets a little bit tiresome after a while. We all know how a star warp drive

13:32.080 --> 13:47.860
works, more or less, or at least we think we do. But to somebody who's never
heard of that before, that can be kind of confusing. Or the intricacies of all

13:47.860 --> 14:02.660
the moralities of robot behavior or the strangeness of time paradoxes. Things
like that can be very confusing to someone first coming to science fiction. So

14:02.660 --> 14:12.860
the stories that I chose for that book were stories that had very simple,
dramatic ideas that were very easy to understand to someone who was not used to

14:12.860 --> 14:22.280
science fiction right away. But that were also very good stories. A more recent
anthology is one carded for the Sierra Club, entitled Dream's Edge, Science

14:22.280 --> 14:31.320
Fiction Stories About the Planet Earth. The origin of that was that the Sierra
Club themselves decided they wanted to publish a science fiction anthology. And

14:31.320 --> 14:42.840
they looked around for someone to do it, and they eventually landed on me. The
main problem I had with that book was that there were too many stories in it

14:42.840 --> 14:49.420
that were downbeat and depressing. If you start writing about the ecology of
Earth, which is what the theme of that was,

14:52.160 --> 15:01.000
well, everything's going wrong these days, as you know. And nobody really has
any answers about what we can do about it. So even though I think all the

15:01.000 --> 15:11.180
stories in there are very good, there are only a few of them that hold out a
whole lot of hope. Most of them are about the problems and the ironies of

15:11.180 --> 15:21.280
messing around with the environment and so on. In 1978, Carr put together an
anthology many people consider his finest. It's called Classic Science Fiction,

15:21.400 --> 15:30.140
The First Golden Age. For this one, Carr chose stories from the years 1940 and
1942, a critical time in the development of modern science fiction. While Carr

15:30.140 --> 15:40.220
selected stories, he did something else that makes the volume of particular
interest. But at the same time, I also did a lot of research on the writers, on

15:40.220 --> 15:48.500
the editors, the publishing companies, the artists, and so forth. The conditions
under which they worked, how much money they were actually able to make. And I

15:48.500 --> 15:57.660
wrote a great deal of introductory material, background material about the
writers and what they were doing, how they came to write each individual story.

15:57.660 --> 16:09.100
And I think the anthology itself contains a number of just classic stories. It's
a basic anthology for anybody's science fiction library. But in addition to

16:09.100 --> 16:18.040
that, that background material is fascinating. It tells a whole lot of things
about how things happened and why they happened. And it also tells a number of

16:18.040 --> 16:26.860
pretty amusing stories about things that went on behind the scenes. I really
enjoyed doing the book. We'll have more with Terry Carr next time.

16:34.080 --> 16:42.160
