16:42.160 --> 16:42.940
Odessa, Texas.

17:32.160 --> 17:36.180
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:52.120 --> 17:57.480
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

18:00.220 --> 18:01.880
And here are your hosts.

18:05.880 --> 18:14.580
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Editor and author Terry Carr has published
three science fiction novels. The first two, Warlord of Kor and Invasion from

18:14.580 --> 18:23.120
2500, go back to the early 1960s and are potboilers in the pulp tradition. But
his most recent novel is a different thing entirely. It's a tightly constructed

18:23.120 --> 18:32.000
work with symbolic and allegorical depth. Entitled Cirque, it was published in
1977. Carr tells us where the idea for the book originated. Cirque is actually

18:32.000 --> 18:45.360
the Bay Area. In some sense anyway, not literally. But the fact is that I live
in the hills of Oakland in the East Bay. And there's a drive along the ridge of

18:45.360 --> 18:59.360
the hills. And I was up there one evening just at dusk. When the light is such
that the bay itself, which you can look down on, you'll see San Francisco and

18:59.360 --> 19:11.380
Marin County across the bay, and San Jose to the south, and Berkeley and Oakland
in front of you, and a lot of water in the middle. But at a particular time of

19:11.380 --> 19:21.100
evening, that water simply turned black. And I was up there looking at that, and
I thought, my God, you can't even tell at the bay. It looks like a gigantic hole

19:21.100 --> 19:31.620
in the ground. And immediately I thought, what would a city be like if it would
build around a gigantic shaft into the earth like that? What effect might that

19:31.620 --> 19:38.000
kind of physical environment have on the psychology of the people who lived in
that city?

19:45.120 --> 19:52.580
Carr explores the psychology and destiny of various inhabitants of the city,
Cirque, during an unusual day's occurrences. On that day, some monsters rise out

19:52.580 --> 19:59.740
of the abyss the city is built around. The monsters are huge and ominous, and
the reaction of Carr's characters to them forms the basis of the book. Near the

19:59.740 --> 20:07.520
end of the novel, the monsters, after threatening the inhabitants of Cirque,
turn into flowers. This episode, along with many others in the book, suggests a

20:07.520 --> 20:17.120
symbolic intent on Carr's part. We asked him if there was deliberate symbolism
in the book. Oh, yes, that is definitely deliberate. I knew the general outline

20:17.120 --> 20:28.460
of the story. I just didn't know the specifics of who was going to do what at
which time and where they were going to be and so on. The symbolism is built

20:28.460 --> 20:41.320
into the whole concept of the story. And I tried not to make that show too much
on the top. You know, I wanted the surface to be a story that was interesting in

20:41.320 --> 20:50.040
and of itself, because I don't believe that symbolism itself should ever try to
carry a story. That bores me to tears. On the other hand, if you have a good

20:50.040 --> 21:03.080
story up front, and beneath that story is symbolism, preferably emotional
symbolism, not just intellectual cuteness, I think that strengthens the story a

21:03.080 --> 21:03.580
good deal.

21:13.580 --> 21:26.620
Carr explains why he chose the title Cirque for the novel. The book, of course,
is about a city which is built around a gigantic chasm into the ground. And so

21:26.620 --> 21:41.600
the city is named Cirque, which is French for circle, and has other connotations
too. It also, for instance, it's the French word for circus. And it was kind of

21:41.600 --> 21:55.020
a circus. There were a whole lot of things, strange things going on at once in
the book. And the construction of the book is circular. It starts at dawn on one

21:55.020 --> 22:07.940
day, and it goes ahead to finish at dawn the next day. And it finishes at the
same place in the city where it began, with the same characters there. So in all

22:07.940 --> 22:19.440
those ways, Cirque or Circle was the perfect title for the book. The only thing
that really had going against it is that nobody knows how to pronounce it. We'll

22:19.440 --> 22:20.840
have more from Terry Carr next time.

