23:54.120 --> 23:55.600
And here are your hosts.

23:59.780 --> 24:07.960
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Science fiction author Terry Carr is noted
for his aliens. One of his better known creations is the mysterious millipede in

24:07.960 --> 24:14.320
the novel Cirque. But he's also written a number of short stories with
fascinating aliens in them. "The Dance of the Changer and the Three" is one of

24:14.320 --> 24:23.180
those stories. Carr provides an explanation of the premise behind the story. I
had been reading, of all people, Roger Zelazny. We seem to be mentioning him a

24:23.180 --> 24:36.440
lot here. And Roger at that time, this was in the late 60s, was working a lot
with mythology in his science fiction. And I got interested in his work. I loved

24:36.440 --> 24:55.960
his work. And I was always interested in mythology itself. And it occurred to me
that mythology tells a whole lot about the fears, the hopes, the beliefs of

24:55.960 --> 25:06.620
humanity. And that indeed, if any alien creatures ever came to this planet and
wanted to find out something about what makes humanity tick, they could do far

25:06.620 --> 25:16.860
worse than to study some of our myths. And I suddenly just, there was a little
click that goes on in your head. And I turned that around and said, well, I like

25:16.860 --> 25:25.860
to think and write about aliens. And it's very difficult to write about an alien
from the inside, because I personally believe that aliens are inexplicable to

25:25.860 --> 25:37.740
us. That we're never going to understand them fully. So I thought, possibly a
good way of dealing with the portrayal of an alien or an entire alien race would

25:37.740 --> 25:48.020
be to do it circuitously by telling an alien myth. And that is exactly what "The
Dance of the Changer and the Three" is, of course, is an alien myth. And the myth

25:48.020 --> 25:51.480
itself is supposed to tell you a lot about the psychology of the race.

25:57.060 --> 26:04.780
We never do understand the psychology of the aliens in the story. The human
narrator describes certain actions and some of the dialogue of the aliens. But

26:04.780 --> 26:12.860
the significance of all of this is never clear. The climax of the story occurs
when the aliens, who are creatures of pure energy, inexplicably destroy almost

26:12.860 --> 26:19.820
all the humans on their planet. And they do it without malice, while they are
performing one of the ritual dances that belong to their mythology. We asked

26:19.820 --> 26:31.420
Carr if there was perhaps some reason for this massacre, something we missed in
reading the story. I don't know, frankly. And I don't want to know. The method

26:31.420 --> 26:47.080
that I used in writing that was since I believed the aliens would be totally un
-understandable to us, because every time the story that I was telling became

26:47.080 --> 26:59.240
too comprehensible, I would write something that made no sense whatever. So that
the myth itself, of course, is kind of a self-canceling myth. If you actually

26:59.240 --> 27:07.720
analyze it, there's a certain circularity to it. It has a dramatic coherence.

27:09.480 --> 27:23.920
But it's not a story that we would ever tell about ourselves that would resonate
with the human psyche. And I wanted to end the story with something totally

27:23.920 --> 27:35.020
inexplicable happening, just to underscore and emphasize the fact that these
creatures were aliens. And I wanted it to be something that none of us was going

27:35.020 --> 27:42.760
to understand. And that meant, inevitably, that I had to be sure I didn't
understand it either. One of the points of the story, then, seems to be that

27:42.760 --> 27:51.700
humans could never understand an alien species. We asked Carr if this
interpretation was correct. Yeah, that was the basic point. Yeah, I've been

27:51.700 --> 27:59.720
trying to make that point in a number of my stories. There's another one that I
wrote earlier called Top Friends, which makes much the same point, but not quite

27:59.720 --> 28:07.500
as dramatically as that does. Carr's premise in "The Dance of the Changer and the
Three" is an interesting one, very different from the common science fiction

28:07.500 --> 28:12.140
notions of aliens as either hostile bug-eyed monsters or as creatures we can
become close to.

